04188nam a22006015i 9780292799677DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221996txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927996777 a10.7560/7469162doi  a(DE-B1597)586657  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0360102bisacsh1 aLadino, Robyn Duff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesegregating Texas Schools :bEisenhower, Shivers, and the Crisis at Mansfield High /cRobyn Duff Ladino. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Pathway to Equality: The Determination to Change -- t2. The Dismantlement of "Separate but Equal" -- t3. The Creed of Segregation and States' Rights in the South with an Emphasis on Texas -- t4. Taking a Stand on School Integration: The Dilemma of President Dwight David Eisenhower during His First Term -- t5. The Mansfield School Integration Case: Jackson v. Rawdon -- t6. A Collision Course: The Crisis at Mansfield High School -- t7. A Significant Aftermath: The Mansfield School Integration Case and Crisis -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the famous Brown v. the Board of Education decisions of 1954 and 1955, the United States Supreme Court ruled that "separate but equal" schools for black and white students were unconstitutional. Yet history records that it took more than a decade of legal battles, civil rights protests, and, tragically, violent confrontations before black students gained full access to previously white schools. Mansfield, Texas, a small community southeast of Fort Worth, was the scene of an early school integration attempt. In this book, Robyn Duff Ladino draws on interviews with surviving participants, media reports, and archival research to provide the first full account of the Mansfield school integration crisis of 1956. Ladino explores how power politics at the local, state, and federal levels ultimately prevented the integration of Mansfield High School in 1956. Her research sheds new light on the actions of Governor Allan Shivers—who, in the eyes of the segregationists, actually validated their cause by his political actions—and it underscores President Dwight Eisenhower's public passivity toward civil rights during his first term of office. Despite the short-term failure, however, the Mansfield school integration crisis helped pave the way for the successful integration of Central High School in Little Rock, Arkansas, in 1957. Thus, it deserves a permanent place in the history of the civil rights movement, which this book amply provides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh1 aBarr, Alwyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Alwyn.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74691640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799677/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK